SIMPLE: hypostasis
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hypostasis
<hw>Hy*pos"ta*sis</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Hypostases</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L., fr. Gr. <?/
subsistence, substance, fr. <?/ to stand under; <?/ under + <?/ to
stand, middle voice of <?/ to cause to stand. See <er>Hypo-</er>, and
<er>Stand</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>That which forms the basis of
anything; underlying principle; a concept or mental entity conceived or
treated as an existing being or thing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Theol.)</fld> <def>Substance; subsistence; essence;
person; personality; -- used by the early theologians to denote any one
of the three subdivisions of the Godhead, the Father, Son, and Holy
Spirit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The Council of Alexandria (<sc>a. d.</sc> 362) defined
<xex>hypostasis</xex> as synonymous with <xex>person</xex>.
<rj><au>Schaff-Herzog.</au></rj></note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Principle; an element; -- used by the alchemists in
speaking of salt, sulphur, and mercury, which they considered as the
three principles of all material bodies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>That which is deposited at the
bottom of a fluid; sediment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hypostasize</ent>⟦br⟧
